TOY HORSE PROJECT

Xiaochun Lai

Background

• Conjoint analysis for toy horse company EarlyRiders

• Dataset
(1)“conjointData”(ratings of different profiles, which refer to different attributes,provided by 200 individuals. Missing value included)
(2)“profilesData” (16 total profiles, attributes includes price(119.99 and 139.99), size(18 and 26 inches),motion(Bouncing and Rocking),style(Racing and Glamour))
(3) “respondentData”(age and gender of 200 individuals)

• Current products(retailers can only sell three products)
EarlyRider: 18 inches glamorous rocking horse(profile 13) and 18 inches racing rocking horse(profile 5), both at 139.99
Competitor: 26 inches racing rocking horse 139.99 (profile 7)

• Mandate
Understanding market preferences in order to reviralize broader product line
Taking advantage of differences across people to target new products or modify existing products to better target segments

Analysis task

A. Use Regression to estimate the conjoint model at the individual level
B. Conduct Benefit Segmentation via Cluster Analysis of Conjoint Part-Utilities
C. Conduct a priori segmentation
D. Simulate market shares for different product-line market scenarios

Part A : Use Regression to estimate the conjoint model at the individual level

• Produce part-utilities to pass to part B
• Produce predictions for missing profiles to pass to part D

#construct a matrix with all profiles information
desmat<-conjointData[,-c(1,2,3)]
atts = c("Low Price","Tall Size","Rocking","Glamour") #list of attributes
colnames(desmat) = atts #each column is a attribute
desmat<-as.matrix(desmat)
head(desmat)

## [1,]         0         0       0       0

## [3,]         0         1       0       0
## [4,]         1         1       0       0
## [5,]         0         0       1       0
## [6,]         1         0       1       0
samplesize<-200 #sample size
ID<-conjointData[,1] #the ID of respondents
ratings<- conjointData[,3] #the rating of respondents

desmatf = cbind(rep(1,nrow(desmat)),desmat); #add column for constant
partworths = matrix(nrow=samplesize,ncol=ncol(desmatf))

#estimate the utility regression for individual
for(i in 1:samplesize){
  partworths[i,]=lm(ratings~desmat,subset=ID==i)$coef
}
colnames(partworths) = c("Intercept",atts)

#predict the missing value of ratings (preparing for market simulation)
partworths.full = matrix(rep(partworths,each=16),ncol=5)
pratings = rowSums(desmatf*partworths.full) #calculate the predicted rating for each individual

#combining actual when available and predicted ratings
finalratings = ifelse(is.na(ratings),pratings,ratings); 
allrat <- conjointData
allrat$ratings <-finalratings

#Runs a set of clusters as kmeans
runClusts <- function(toClust,nClusts,print=TRUE,maxClusts=15,seed=12345,nstart=20,iter.max=100){
  if(length(nClusts)>4){
    warning("Using only first 4 elements of nClusts.")
  }
  kms=list(); ps=list();
  for(i in 1:length(nClusts)){
    kms[[i]] <- kmeans(toClust,nClusts[i],iter.max = iter.max, nstart=nstart)
    ps[[i]] <- fviz_cluster(kms[[i]], geom = "point", data = toClust) + ggtitle(paste("k =",nClusts[i]))
   
  }
  library(gridExtra)
  if(print){
    tmp <- marrangeGrob(ps, nrow = 2,ncol=2)
    print(tmp)
  }
  list(kms=kms,ps=ps)
}
cluster <- runClusts(toClust,c(2,3,4))

#Two and Three segmentation are better
#Plot the clusters

plotClust <- function(km,toClust,
                     discPlot=FALSE,standardize=TRUE,margins = c(7,4,4,2)){
  nc <- length(km$size)
  percsize <- paste(1:nc," = ",format(km$size/sum(km$size)*100,digits=2),"%",sep="")
  pie(km$size,labels=percsize,col=1:nc)
  
  gg <- fviz_cluster(km, geom = "point", data = toClust) + ggtitle(paste("k =",nc))
  print(gg)
  
  if(discPlot){
    plotcluster(toClust, km$cluster,col=km$cluster);
  }
  if(standardize){
    kmc <- (km$centers-rep(colMeans(toClust),each=nc))/rep(apply(toClust,2,sd),each=nc)
    rng <- range(kmc)
    dist <- rng[2]-rng[1]
    locs <- kmc+.05*dist*ifelse(kmc>0,1,-1)
    par(mar=margins)
    bm <- barplot(kmc,col=1:nc,beside=TRUE,las=2,main="Cluster Means",ylim=rng+dist*c(-.1,.1))
    text(bm,locs,formatC(kmc,format="f",digits=1))
  } else {
    rng <- range(km$centers)
    dist <- rng[2]-rng[1]
    locs <- km$centers+.05*dist*ifelse(km$centers>0,1,-1)
    bm <- barplot(km$centers,beside=TRUE,col=1:nc,main="Cluster Means",ylim=rng+dist*c(-.1,.1))
    text(bm,locs,formatC(km$centers,format="f",digits=1))
  }
  vs <- data.table(Segment = 1:nrow(km$centers),km$centers,Size = km$size/sum(km$size))
  vs[order(-Size),]
}

plotClust(cluster$kms[[1]],toClust,FALSE,FALSE)

#function to estimate the choice of consumer
simFCShares = function(scen,data){ 
  inmkt = data[scen] #construct the subsetted matrix of options
  bestOpts = apply(inmkt,1,max)  #identify which option is best = min value
  tb=(inmkt==bestOpts)*1 #Create table with best options with 1's or 0's
  tb=t(apply(tb,1, function(x) x/sum(x)))
  shs=colSums(tb)/sum(tb)
  shs
}

# for loop to calculate market share
simScenarios = function(scenarios,data){
  res = matrix(nrow=length(scenarios),ncol=length(data)) 
  for(i in 1:length(scenarios)){ 
    res[i, scenarios[[i]] ] = simFCShares(scenarios[[i]],data)
  }
  res = as.data.frame(res); names(res) = names(data) 
  res 
}

#Calculate market share for each product

#predict profit
for (i in 1:nrow(profilesData)){
  if(profilesData$priceLabel[i] == 119.99){
    profilesData$wholesaleprice[i] <- 95.99
  }else{
    profilesData$wholesaleprice[i] <- 111.99
  }
  if(profilesData$sizeLabel[i] == "18 inches" & profilesData$motionLabel[i] == "Rocking"){
    profilesData$vcost[i]<-33
  }
  if(profilesData$sizeLabel[i] == "26 inches" & profilesData$motionLabel[i] == "Rocking"){
    profilesData$vcost[i]<-41
  }
  if(profilesData$sizeLabel[i] == "18 inches" & profilesData$motionLabel[i] == "Bouncing"){
    profilesData$vcost[i]<-38
  }
  if(profilesData$sizeLabel[i] == "26 inches" & profilesData$motionLabel[i] == "Bouncing"){
    profilesData$vcost[i]<-46
  }
  profilesData$profit[i]=  profilesData$wholesaleprice[i] - profilesData$vcost[i]
}

mktsize<-4000
simProfit = function(myProds,data,comProds,initialProds,fcosts,startupcosts){
  scen<-c(myProds,comProds)
  mktS<-simFCShares(c(myProds,comProds),data)
  mktS<-mktS[1:2]
  profile<-as.data.frame(profilesData[myProds,]) 
  vprofit<-mktS* profile$profit*mktsize - fcosts 
  new<- length(myProds) - sum(myProds %in% initialProds) 
  print(sum(vprofit)-startupcosts*new)
  }
